<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Breadcrumb</strong> shows the user's location within a site or data hierarchy as a structured
  trail — an ordered list of links from the root to the current page. It answers <em>"where am I?"</em>,
  which is a different question from a navigation menu (<em>"where can I go?"</em>), tabs
  (<em>"which panel?"</em>), or a stepper (<em>"how far through this process?"</em>).
</p>
<p>
  Native-first by construction: a breadcrumb <em>is</em>
  <code>&lt;nav aria-label="Breadcrumb"&gt;</code> wrapping an <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code> of <code>&lt;a&gt;</code>
  links, with the current page a non-link node carrying <code>aria-current="page"</code>. The block adds
  only what that markup cannot express alone: <strong>overflow collapse</strong> and
  <strong>responsible label truncation</strong>. It composes the
  <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation Intent</a> (it is a navigation landmark) and the
  <a href="/intents/typography/">Typography Intent</a> (truncating a long crumb label).
</p>

