<h2>Structure (the native baseline)</h2>
{% highlight "html" %}
<nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
  <ol>
    <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/products">Products</a></li>
    <li><a aria-current="page">Widgets</a></li>   <!-- current: non-link -->
  </ol>
</nav>
<!-- separators come from CSS (li + li::before { content: "›" }), never the DOM -->
{% endhighlight %}

<h2>Behaviour the block adds</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Overflow collapse.</strong> When the trail is wider than its container, the middle collapses behind a single disclosure (an ellipsis crumb that reveals the hidden ancestors); the root and current crumbs stay visible.</li>
  <li><strong>Responsible truncation.</strong> A long individual crumb label truncates via the <a href="/intents/typography/">Typography Intent</a>'s shared paradigm (the same one tabs, chips, and table cells use) — with the full text recoverable.</li>
  <li><strong>Presentational separators.</strong> The divider between crumbs is CSS-generated or <code>aria-hidden</code>, so AT reads the list as an ordered trail, not "Home slash Products slash Widgets".</li>
</ul>

<h2>Boundaries</h2>
<p>
  Distinct from <a href="/blocks/nav-list/">nav-list</a> (APG Disclosure Navigation menus), tabs (panel
  switching), and <a href="/blocks/stepper/">stepper</a> (a linear process). A breadcrumb is a
  <em>location trail</em> — it composes the Navigation Intent but is its own pattern, cross-referenced
  rather than folded into nav-list.
</p>
